Dear developer. The audio icon in the bar in the bottom of the screen is not activated. How can I activate it? Can it play audio files of the installed .bgl dictionaries? I have a unique .bgl dictionary which, unlike other .bgl dictionaries, displays its own audio icon in Babylon Software interface on Windows, which when clicked plays the corresponding human-voice .wav file located in a special folder with specific name and destination. This is not the case in the GoldenDict.

Actually, GoldenDict is the most useful and advanced dictionary app. It supports lots of dictionary formats, audio pronunciations, lots of customization, night mode.The only thing I miss is a pop up window support. It currently opens only in full screen mode.It would be great, if we could select a word on a e-book and open its definition in a pop up window. EDIT: I sent a support e-mail about the app can't see dictionary folder in sdcard or in internal phone with Android 10 (it was also reported (#1256) in their git bug tracker). They responded quickly to the e-mail and solved the problem. Many thanks to the support team.

Before this great app begins to drown in the 1‚òÖ ratings, let me explain the problem we're facing: the culprit is either Android System Webview or Chrome. Both were recently updated and GoldenDict uses either one of these Webviews to display its content. The ONLY solution is either to uninstall the last update of Chrome or ASW and reinstall the previous version, or restore the factory versions that came bundled with your phone and do NOT update it. Once that's done, GoldenDict will work as usual

Read if your GD stopped working! A recent Google's update to Webview (also part of Chrome) breaks GD so that dictionary articles are no longer displayed. Try to uninstall or disable Chrome, uninstall Webview update in PlayStore, and don't allow Play Store to update it automatically. This is the only way I could fix my GD. Google may fix this in the future but until then don't use their latest Chrome or Webview update.

bug fix request: on Blackberry KeyOne, which has a physical QWERTY 
keyboard, when focussing the search field and then pressing the alt+enter 
combination (which switches the typing language), the field de-focuses by 
itself. most probably the program simply detects the press of the enter key 
(without understanding that it is just a part of a combination), and does 
what it normally does when enter alone is pressed. at the same time, there 
must exist a way to differentiate these two situations in Android, for even 
Play Store does not have this bug in its search field. maybe the solution 
is to detect not a press of the enter key, but an "\n" symbol input? 
another request is to make the search field focussed by default when the 
program starts or is brought foreground, or even basically always ‚Äî because 
with a physical keyboard it is intuitively logical to be able to just start 
typing a new word anytime when the dictionary is on-screen (just as the 
Windows version of Lingvo does), whithout first tapping on the search field 
each time. (although this might be better made optional, for on regular 
thouch-screen phones this might lead to virtual keyboard being on the 
screen all the time, covering half of the screen)
